    "summary": "Ptolemy I Soter ('Savior', r. 305–282 BC) was one of Alexander the Great's most trusted generals who, through shrewd diplomacy and opportunism during the [[event:1039|Wars of the Diadochi]], secured Egypt and founded the [[event:1040|Ptolemaic Kingdom]] that would last for nearly three centuries. He was present at Alexander's side throughout the campaigns and later wrote a history of Alexander's campaigns (now lost) that served as one of the best primary sources for later biographers.\n\nDuring the Diadochi conflicts, Ptolemy consistently pursued a defensive strategy — securing Egypt's natural borders (the desert and the sea) rather than attempting to reconquer Alexander's full empire. He diverted Alexander's body from Perdiccas, burying it in Alexandria as a dynastic legitimizing symbol. He organized the [[event:1044|Library of Alexandria]] and the Mouseion, establishing the pattern of royal patronage of scholarship that would define the Ptolemaic dynasty. Before his death, he abdicated in favor of his son Ptolemy II, the first ruler in the Hellenistic world to do so, ensuring a smooth succession — reflecting the administrative pragmatism that characterized his reign.",
